One winter morning in Johannesburg, South Africa, a few years ago, I was driving to work to find the city shrouded in haze.
I drive past there almost every day, but this time was unusual, a sight I had never seen before.
Johannesburg is known for its distinctively beautiful skyline, but it was barely visible that morning.
I soon realized that what I was seeing was precisely the severe haze caused by air pollution.
The contrast between that beautiful environment I knew in old days and the now hazy skyline rippled through my mind.
I feared that there was a good chance that the once colorful sunset view would be swallowed up by the gloomy haze.
In that moment, I felt a strong urge to do something, but I didn’t know what to do.
All I knew was that I couldn’t just stand by.
The biggest challenge was that I didn’t know the science of the environment—air quality management, or atmospheric chemistry.
I was a computer engineer, and I was pretty sure that I couldn’t solve the problem of atmospheric pollution by coding.
(Laughter) In what capacity would I tackle this problem?
I was nothing more than a small city man.
Over the next few years, I learned an important lesson that we should all take to heart if we want to achieve a better future.
Even if you are not an expert in a particular field, your expertise may contain solutions to problems in that field.
Sometimes the unique perspective you hold can spur unconventional thinking to sway the situation, but you need to be bold and try.
Only then will you know the outcome.
What I knew at the time was that if I wanted to try to change, I had to know enough about pollution first, so I went back as a student.
I did some basic research and quickly learned that air pollution is the world’s greatest environmental health risk.
World Health Organization data shows that in 2012, almost 14% of deaths worldwide were caused by atmospheric pollution in and around households, which is especially common in low- and middle-income countries.
Air pollution is responsible for a higher death rate each year than malaria and AIDS.
In Africa, premature deaths from unsafe sanitation, or deaths from malnutrition of children, pale in the face of air pollution, while it also comes with huge economic costs: according to the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development, in 2013, more than $400 billion was spent by interested parties.
In my work, I explore the technological frontiers of artificial intelligence, including the symbiotic relationship between humans and machines, find beneficial footholds and help us make better decisions.
When I thought about air pollution again, things became clear on how to manage it, and we needed to find better ways to make better decisions Considering the size of the problem, collaboration was very necessary.
So I decided to get to know some people working in this field.
I started talking to officials in Johannesburg and other surrounding cities, I joined the local scientific community, and I made some phone calls to completely strange but related people.
These experiences I set out to intervene helped me to understand the problem more deeply.
It also helped me avoid the trap that people in my line sometimes fall into when they try to innovate: adopting a technology quickly, before really grasping the problem.
I started thinking, what can I do to improve this situation?
I started asking myself how to effectively combine my knowledge skills in software engineering and artificial intelligence with the expertise of the people I connect with.
I wanted to create an online air quality management platform to reveal future pollution trends, make relevant predictions to judge what might happen.
I was sure my idea could become a realistic solution, but also faced with uncertainty, and I couldn’t guarantee it would be successful.
All I had was a specific set of engineer skills, the skills I gained from my work.(Laughter) Of course, for someone who has been working in the air pollution field for years, my skills were completely new.
I came to realise that sometimes a novel perspective, a new skill set, can spawn something remarkable.
Our willpower and imagination is a light that shows us beyond obstacles and open a new chapter.
I took a deeper look at the air pollution problem, looking for air pollution data from the past dozen years, and meteorological data in and around Johannesburg.After that, with my colleagues in South Africa and China, I created an air quality resolution support system and uploaded it to the cloud.
This software is able to analyse historical and real-time data to reveal trends in pollution over time and space.
We then use new machine learning techniques to predict future pollution scenarios days in advance.
This means residents can make better decisions about their daily itineraries and where to settle with their families.
We can anticipate adverse pollution events in advance, delineating sources of severe pollution, allowing relevant authorities to issue directives to adjust their operations.
With assisted scenario planning, city planners can also make better decisions on how to scale up infrastructure work, such as residential placement in industrial areas.
We have set up a pilot pilot of this technology, running for 120 days, covering the whole of South Africa.
Our expected results are validated.The forecast data we show and the data we collect in the field show a strong correlation.
Through our management, we have brought in world-leading cutting-edge instruments to predict atmospheric quality with unprecedented resolution and accuracy, allowing the city I was driving into on a winter morning not long ago to benefit.At that point I said to myself, “Something is not right, I have to figure out how to do something about it.”
