A lot of people think that driving a car is something that only those who can see can do.
And blind people wanting to drive a car alone and safely has also been considered an impossible task until now.
Hey everyone, my name is Dennis Hong, and we made a car for blind people for freedom and independence that is designed for people with visual impairments.
Before I tell about this car for blind people, let me briefly talk about another project I did once called the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency Urban Challenge.
It was about building a mechanical car that could drive itself.
You press the start button, you don’t touch anything anymore, and it also gets to its destination completely autonomously.
In the 2007 challenge, our team won $500,000 to get third place in the competition.
Probably that time, the National Association of the Blind, or the Blind Association, challenged the design team about who could design a car that blind people could drive independently and safely.
We felt like we were going to try it because we felt, hey, where is this going to be hard.
We already had a car that was autonomous.
We just let blind people do it inside and drive it, and it wouldn’t be done, right?
(Laughter) But we weren’t so wrong.
What the Blind Association wanted was not a car that could carry blind people around, but a car that blind people could actively make choices and drive.
So we had to give up everything we had and start from scratch.
To test this crazy idea, we designed a prototype of a small sand truck to test its feasibility.
In the summer of 2009, we invited a lot of blind youth across the country and gave them a second chance to use this car for a ride.
It was definitely a cool experience.
But the problem with this car was that it was designed to allow blind people to drive only in very limited environments, like a closed parking lot — even on a road made of red traffic cones.
So with this success, we decided to take the important next step and make a real car that can drive on the road.
So how does it work?
Well, it’s a relatively complex system, but let me explain, to simplify it.
We have three stages.
We have a sensing stage, a computing stage, and a non-visual interface.
So the driver is obviously invisible, and the system has to be able to sense the surroundings and collect data for the driver.
At this point, we use an initial metering element.
It measures acceleration, angular acceleration -- just like the human ear, the inner ear.
I combine this information with a global positioning system to predict where the vehicle is.
We also use two cameras to detect the path of the vehicle.
We also use three laser rangefinders.
The laser scans the environment to detect obstacles -- vehicles passing by from the front, from the rear and also any obstacles on the road, any obstacles around the vehicle.
All this massive information is then aggregated into a computer, which does two things.
First, one thing is to process information to understand the surrounding environment -- which are the driving paths and which are obstacles -- and translate that information to the driver.
This system is also very intelligent to figure out the safest driving path.
We are also able to give instructions on how to operate the running program of the vehicle.
But the question is: how can we transmit information and instructions to a blind man fast enough and accurate enough to make sure he can drive?
For this, we have designed a lot of different non-visual user interface technologies.
The original three-dimensional flat sound system, the vibrating vest, the voice-activated gear, the leg straps, even the shoes that put pressure on the feet.
But today we're talking about three of these non-visual user interface technologies.
The first interface is called the driving handle.
It's a pair of gloves, and in the knuckles it has vibration elements, by which you can transmit instructions on how to drive -- direction and amplitude.
Another device is called a speed shock belt.
This car seat -- it's actually a massage chair.
We take it out and we reassemble the vibration elements of different patterns.We let them transmit speed information, but also instructions on how to use the accelerator and brakes.
Here you can see how the computer understands the surroundings.Because you can't see the vibration, we actually put red LEDs on the driver, so he can see what's happening.
This is the sensed data, and this is transmitted from the sensor into the computer.
So these two devices, the driving handle and the speed shock belt, are very effective.
But the problem is that these are the instruction devices.
So it's not really freedom in the sense, right?
The computer tells you how to drive -- turn left, turn right, accelerate, brake.
I call this the co-pilot problem.
So we're avoiding implied instruction devices and focusing more on the information devices.
A typical example of this kind of non-visual information interface is called an empty map.
Think of this as a display for a blind person.
It’s a small desktop with a lot of holes on it, compressed air is excluded from it, and with this it can be described as a picture.
So even if you’re blind, you put your hand on it, you sense the course of the road and obstacles.
In fact, you can also change the frequency of the air released and possibly also the temperature.
This is actually a multi-dimensional user interface.
Here, you can see the cameras on the left and right and how the computer parses and transmits this information to the empty map.
And just like that, we’re showing a simulation program where a blind person is driving with an empty map.
This program can be a great help in training blind drivers and quickly testing different theories in terms of different kinds of non-visual user interfaces.
That’s basically how it works.
But this car is a model car, and it won’t be on the road either unless it proves to be as safe to drive as today’s cars, or safer.
I truly believe that this will happen.
But does society, can they accept this radical idea?
How are we going to deal with insurance?
How are we going to issue a driver’s license?
Behind the technological challenges there are a lot of different obstacles that we need to address before it actually becomes a reality.
