Today I want to show you the way we make things in the future.
I believe soon our buildings and machines will be able to self-assemble, self-replicate and self-heal.
So I'm going to show you what I think is the current state of manufacturing, and then compare it to some natural systems.
So in current manufacturing we have skyscrapers -- two and a half years, 500,000 to millions of parts, very complex, using new technologies in steel and concrete and glass.
We have exciting machines that can take us into space -- five years, two and a half million parts.
But on the other hand, if you look at natural systems, we have two million types of proteins that fold in ten thousand nanoseconds, and we can replicate DNA with three billion base pairs in about an hour.
That's the complexity of our natural systems, but they're very efficient, more efficient than anything we build, more complex than anything we can build.
They're more energy efficient.
They rarely make mistakes.
They self-heal to stay long-lived.
There's something super interesting about natural systems.
If we can translate that into our built environment, there's a lot of potential in the way we build things.
I think the key is self-assembly.
If we want to utilize self-assembly in our own physical environment, I think there are four key factors.
The first is that we need to decode the complexity of all the things we're building -- that is, our buildings and our machines.
We need to decode them into simple sequences -- basically the DNA of how our buildings operate.
Then we need the programmable parts that can accept that sequence and be used to fold or reshape.
We need some energy to activate, to allow our parts to fold up according to a program.
We need some type of error-correcting redundancy to guarantee that what we build successfully is what we want.
So I'm going to show you guys some of the projects my colleagues and I are working on to achieve this self-assembled future.
The first two projects are MacroBot and DeciBot.
These projects are all large-scale reconfigurable robots -- proteins that are 8 feet, 12 feet long.
They're embedded in electromechanical devices, sensors.
You need to decode the way you want to fold into, decode into a series of angles -- negative 120 degrees, negative 120 degrees, 0 degrees, 0 degrees, 120 degrees, negative 120 degrees -- things like that; a series of angles, or turns, you can pass this over with a wire.
Each unit gets its own message — like minus 120. It does a spin, checks to see if it spins in place and then passes the sequence to its neighbors.
There are many brilliant scientists, engineers, designers working on this project.
I think this project really reveals: Is this really scalable?
I mean, spend thousands of dollars many man-hours to build this eight foot robot.
Can we really scale it up and can we really embed the robot in every part?
The next question is look at passivity, or passively try to make reorganization programmable.
But it goes a step further, it tries to do the actual calculations.
Basically embeds the basic building blocks of most computation, digital logic gates, directly into the parts.
This is a NAND gate.
Each gate to be used for computation has a tetrahedron on it, two input tetrahedra.
One of them is an input from the user, like you are building a brick.
The other is an input to a brick that you put before you come.
Then it gives an output in three-dimensional space.
That means the user stacks the bricks the way they want.
It computes based on what it did before and your instructions.
Now it starts moving in three-dimensional space — up or down.
Look, the input of [1,1] is equal to 0, which means down, on the left.
On the right, the input of [0,0] is 1 and the output is up.
So what this really means is that we have a blueprint in our structure that we now want to build.
So the information about what we want to build is all embedded in it.
That means we have some form of self-replication.
To this situation, I call it self-directed replication, because you have an exact blueprint in your structure.
If you get an error, you can replace a section.
All the local information is embedded in it, telling you how to fix it.
So you have something that you can climb, and it reads the output one by one.
It is directly embedded;
